d ωx 6= ω′ x at a point x ∈ M , then (ω′ x − ωx) ∧ Ωx = 0 and hence Ωx = (ω′ x − ωx)∧ α for some α ∈ T ∗ xM , but this contradicts the non-degeneracy of Ω at the point x. Remark 3. If (Ω, ω) is an l.c.s. structure onM and a ∈ C∞(M,R) then (eΩ, ω−da) is again an l.c.s. structure on M . Two l.c.s. structures (Ω, ω) and (Ω′, ω′) on M are called conformally equivalent if (Ω′, ω′) = (eΩ, ω − da) for some a ∈ C∞(M,R). We will write (Ω, ω) ∼ (Ω′, ω′) in this case. Note that the canonic orientation does only depend on the conformal equivalence class of (M,Ω, ω). Remark 4. Suppose ω is a 1-form on M and consider the trivial line bundle E := M × R → M with the connection ∇Xf := X · f + ω(X)f . For its curvature one easily checks R∇ ω = dω. Via the obvious identification Ω∗(M ;E) = Ω∗(M) the covariant exterior derivative of E-valued differential forms is d∇ ω = d. For closed ω one has dd = 0, corresponding to the fact that the connection ∇ is flat in this case. Moreover, for two 1-forms ω1 and ω2 one has d12(α ∧ β) = (d1α) ∧ β + (−1)|α|α ∧ (d2β), (1) which corresponds to the fact ∇1 ⊗∇2 = ∇12 . 1991 Mathematics Subject Classification. 53D99.","arxiv_id":null,"doi":"10.1142/9789812777089_0007","journal_title":"undefined"},"created_by":null,"proposed_to":[],"id":null,"created_at":{"$date":"2021-07-27T14:18:51.409Z"},"cited_articles":[{"$binary":"Z/HL2vMpTyiW3YqgNUslgA==","$type":"4"}]},{"_id":{"$oid":"610015cbd112b71809959a59"},"asset_id":{"$binary":"SCvGVCmJQE2bxteIz+wl7Q==","$type":"4"},"payload":{"title":"Some properties of locally conformal symplectic structures","authors":["A. Banyaga"],"date":{"$date":"2002-07-27T00:00:00.000Z"},"pdf_url":"https://doi.org/10.1007/S00014-002-8345-Z","abstract":"Abstract. We show that the \n$ d_{\\omega} $-cohomology is isomorphic to a conformally invariant usual de Rham cohomology of an appropriate cover. We also prove a Moser theorem for locally conformal symplectic (lcs) forms. We point out a connection between lcs geometry and contact ge