f the future (and considered bad omens today), were of such a general nature that they were difficult to apply to daily life, for instance sightings of black cats that foretold bad luck. Many legends and ancient mythologies recount attempts to deal with such portents. For instance, the Persian tale, where a gardener’s encounter with Death causes him to flee to Isfahan but Death is actually on the way there, to collect the gardener so is surprised to see him before his hour. Other stories tell of individuals who had strong foresight but, like Cassandra of Troy, were never believed. The Romans approached the matter in a logical fashion and asked only yes or no questions of their augurs, who were able to indicate whether a certain day was favorable to go to battle by looking at the entrails of a freshly slaughtered animal. In modern science, which may itself be defined as predicting future events from observing past occurrences, some areas are more successful than others. Simple Newtonian laws suffice to accurately predict the time it takes an apple to fall from a tree to the ground, or the braking distance of a car of a certain weight going a certain speed, while economics may boast spectacular failures, without any stock exchange crash or economic crisis having been predicted. Modern medicine resides somewhere between bad omens and Roman augurs, while those involved in public health may sometimes feel akin to Cassandra when they witness a new generation taking up smoking. Genetic research has brought us many omens: a variant may be bad luck, but it is unknown if and whether it will have an effect, and there is nothing one can do about it. Prediction models are the result of sophisticated mathematical models designed to answer the yes or no question as to who will develop, or already has, a disease. Over the years, the number of publications in medicine with such prediction scores has risen dramatically, as Fig. 1 shows. The Journal of Thrombosis and Haemostasis has also published a number of articles with prediction scores. In this October issue, the VISION investigators report on prediction of stroke in patients with atrial fibrillation undergoing surgery: a clinically relevant dilemma, for nearly 5% died or suffered a stroke in the 30 days following surgery. There were differences in the predictive power of the four scoring tools that were compared, which is useful knowledge. The question that remains, and that has echoes from antiquity, is whether it is useful to predict. This will only be the case when we have methods to protect those at increased risk, or if we can avoid certain surgeries. A more philosophical question is whether there is a theoretical maximum in prediction. As we cannot monitor people on a daily basis, supposing we even knew what aspects to monitor, there will always remain apparently random events that are unpredictable, yet at the heart of the matter, there still may be some principle to this randomness. Fig. 1. The growing trend of medical publications with prediction scores from 1996 to 2015. Data extracted from the Web of Science using TOPIC ‘prediction score’ AND TOPIC ‘medicine or medical or biomedical’; refined by: DOCUMENT TYPES ‘article’; indexes = SCI-EXPANDED, A&HCI; timespan = 1996–2015.","arxiv_id":null,"doi":"10.1111/jth.13127","journal_title":"undefined"},"created_by":null,"proposed_to":[],"id":null,"created_at":{"$date":"2021-07-28T12:22:35.835Z"},"cited_articles":[{"$binary":"bZVftihtTxycA2XO0fxS5g==","$type":"4"}]},{"_id":{"$oid":"61014c0bd112b71809959af8"},"asset_id":{"$binary":"00pvn84JQA2FP78r5ZVVIg==","$type":"4"},"payload":{"title":"Incremental Learning of Daily Routines as Workflows in a Smart Home Environment","authors":["B. D. Carolis","S. Ferilli","Domenico Redavid"],"date":{"$date":"2015-07-28T00:00:00.000Z"},"pdf_url":"http://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=2675063","abstract":"Smart home environments should proactively support users in their activities, anticipating their needs according to their preferences. Understanding what the user is doing in the environment is important for adapting the environment's behavior, as well as for identifying situations that could be problematic for the user. Enabling the environment to exploit models of the user's most common behaviors is an important step toward this objective. In particular, models of the daily routines of a user can be exploited not only for predicting his/her needs, but also for comparing the actual situation at a given moment with the expected one, in order to detect anomalies in his/her behavior. While manually setting up process models in business and factory environments may be cost-effective, building models of the processes involved in people's everyday life is infeasible. This fact fully justifies the interest of the Ambient Intelligence community in automatically learning such models from examples of actual behavior. Incremental adaptation of the models and the ability to express/learn complex conditions on the involved tasks are also desirable. This article describes how process mining can be used for learning users’ daily routines from a dataset of annotated sensor data. The solution that we propose relies on a First-Order Logic learning approach. Indeed, First-Order Logic provides a single, comprehensive and powerful framework for supporting all the previously mentioned features. Our experiments, performed both on a proprietary toy dataset and on publicly available real-world ones, indicate that this approach is efficient and effective for learning and modeling daily routines in Smart Home Environments.","arxiv_id":null,"doi":"10.1145/2675063","journal_title":"undefined"},"created_by":null,"proposed_to":[],"id":null,"created_at":{"$date":"2021-07-28T12:22:35.837Z"},"cited_articles":[{"$binary":"bZVftihtTxycA2XO0fxS5g==","$type":"4"}]},{"_id":{"$oid":"61014c1ad112b71809959af9"},"asset_id":{"$binary":"HBXlgWxCR+ujvL2WkwOupw==","$type":"4"},"payload":{"title":"Extreme Learning Machine for Multilayer Perceptron","authors":["Jiexiong Tang","Chenwei Deng","Guangbin Huang"],"date":{"$date":"2016-07-28T00:00:00.000Z"},"pdf_url":"http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/stamp/stamp.jsp?tp=&arnumber=7103337","abstract":"Extreme learning machine (ELM) is an emerging learning algorithm for the generalized single hidden layer feedforward neural networks, of which the hidden node parameters are randomly generated and the output weights are analytically computed. However, due to its shallow architecture, feature learning using ELM may not be effective for natural signals (e.g., images/videos), even with a large number of hidden nodes. To address this issue, in this paper, a new ELM-based hierarchical learning framework is proposed for multilayer perceptron. The proposed architecture is divided into two main components: 1) self-taught feature extraction followed by supervised feature classification and 2) they are bridged by random initialized hidden weights. The novelties of this paper are as follows: 1) unsupervised multilayer encoding is conducted for feature extraction, and an ELM-based sparse autoencoder is developed via ℓ1 constraint. By doing so, it achieves more compact and meaningful feature representations than the original ELM; 2) by exploiting the advantages of ELM random feature mapping, the hierarchically encoded outputs are randomly projected before final decision making, which leads to a better generalization with faster learning speed; and 3) unlike the greedy layerwise training of deep learning (DL), the hidden layers of the proposed framework are trained in a forward manner. Once the previous layer is established, the weights of the current layer are fixed without fine-tuning. Therefore, it has much better learning efficiency than the DL. Extensive experiments on various widely used classification data sets show that the proposed algorithm achieves better and faster convergence than the existing state-of-the-art hierarchical learning methods. Fu