 contain information with which they disagree. Implications and directions for future research are discussed.","arxiv_id":null,"doi":"10.1111/J.1083-6101.2009.01440.X","journal_title":"undefined"},"created_by":null,"proposed_to":[],"id":null,"created_at":{"$date":"2021-07-28T15:10:38.110Z"},"cited_articles":[]},{"_id":{"$oid":"6101736ed112b71809959b71"},"asset_id":{"$binary":"PY9EfJ/mTL2nV5zKupzpWQ==","$type":"4"},"payload":{"title":"How Has the Literature on Gini's Index Evolved in the Past 80 Years?","authors":["Kuan Xu"],"date":{"$date":"2003-07-28T00:00:00.000Z"},"pdf_url":"https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=423200","abstract":"The Gini coefficient or index is perhaps one of the most used indicators of social and economic conditions. From its first proposal in English in 1921 to the present, a large number of papers on the Gini index has been written and published. Going through these papers represents a demanding task. The aim of this survey paper is to help the reader to navigate through the major developments of the literature and to incorporate recent theoretical research results with a particular focus on different formulations and interpretations of the Gini index, its social welfare implication, and source and subgroup decomposition.","arxiv_id":null,"doi":"10.2139/ssrn.423200","journal_title":"undefined"},"created_by":null,"proposed_to":[],"id":null,"created_at":{"$date":"2021-07-28T15:10:38.227Z"},"cited_articles":[]},{"_id":{"$oid":"6101736ed112b71809959b72"},"asset_id":{"$binary":"Pq8JBJGgRg+JG1vTbdyPYg==","$type":"4"},"payload":{"title":"The Law of Group Polarization","authors":["C. Sunstein"],"date":{"$date":"1999-07-28T00:00:00.000Z"},"pdf_url":"https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=199668","abstract":"In a striking empirical regularity, deliberation tends to move groups, and the individuals who compose them, toward a more extreme point in the direction indicated by their own predeliberation judgments. For example, pe