 different coding approaches and problem variations on anonymization quality and performance. To our knowledge, this is the first result demonstrating optimal k-anonymization of a non-trivial dataset under a general model of the problem.","arxiv_id":null,"doi":"10.1109/ICDE.2005.42","journal_title":"undefined"},"created_by":null,"proposed_to":[],"related_articles_were_imported":false,"id":null,"created_at":{"$date":"2021-08-02T11:21:59.161Z"},"cited_articles":[{"$binary":"i3jn3CmpT4eEMaqYlgs5yg==","$type":"4"},{"$binary":"EKkY4oXFQQmEdZXF/SjKlQ==","$type":"4"}]},{"_id":{"$oid":"6107d557942a4b6254576ffa"},"asset_id":{"$binary":"LL5jGrAsTc6YPqvcNgxGCA==","$type":"4"},"payload":{"title":"Introduction to Statistical Relational Learning","authors":["Charles Sutton","A. McCallum"],"date":{"$date":"2007-08-02T00:00:00.000Z"},"pdf_url":"https://doi.org/10.7551/mitpress%2F7432.001.0001","abstract":"Semantic Scholar extracted view of ","arxiv_id":null,"doi":"10.7551/mitpress/7432.001.0001","journal_title":"undefined"},"created_by":null,"proposed_to":[],"related_articles_were_imported":false,"id":null,"created_at":{"$date":"2021-08-02T11:21:59.260Z"},"cited_articles":[{"$binary":"qxReDZ0bSzuQMrZKip4ozQ==","$type":"4"}]},{"_id":{"$oid":"6107d557942a4b6254576ffb"},"asset_id":{"$binary":"MMTThV21QrqJlVds3npFSg==","$type":"4"},"payload":{"title":"Differential Privacy","authors":["C. Dwork"],"date":{"$date":"2006-08-02T00:00:00.000Z"},"pdf_url":"https://doi.org/10.1007/11787006_1","abstract":"In 1977 Dalenius articulated a desideratum for statistical databases: nothing about an individual should be learnable from the database that cannot be learned without access to the database. We give a general impossibility result showing that a formalization of Dalenius' goal along the lines of semantic security cannot be achieved. Contrary to intuition, a variant of the result threatens the privacy even of someone not in the database. This state of affairs suggests a new measure, differential privacy, which, intuitively, captures the increased risk to one's privacy incurred by participating in a database. The techniques developed in a sequence of papers [8, 13, 3], culminating in those described in [12], can achieve any desired level of privacy under this measure. In many cases, extremely accurate information about the database can be provided while simultaneously ensuring very high levels of privacy","arxiv_id":null,"doi":"10.1007/11787006_1","journal_title":"undefined"},"created_by":null,"proposed_to":[],"related_articles_were_imported":true,"id":null,"created_at":{"$date":"2021-08-02T11:21:59.393Z"},"cited_articles":[{"$binary":"8vvs5JulT0Kg21KDJcZUhQ==","$type":"4"},{"$binary":"is5Ld28hSMGZtIzAhHw/mA==","$type":"4"},{"$binary":"Wnnm/tTySqm8ekRNNMyXIg==","$type":"4"},{"$binary":"ZUoxWxdBQ76wZXQoFj42gA==","$type":"4"},{"$binary":"jj3iV3OdQ56xAJJGXsJPqg==","$type":"4"},{"$binary":"+hTjzb/8TgeLBvM9T/6QbQ==","$type":"4"},{"$binary":"y9IECsq8SOagFqVCFDeDAw==","$type":"4"},{"$binary":"gJv0ITk/Sbqbm1z09mBnZA==","$type":"4"},{"$binary":"H21xwDazRxGijJ/fqE41Vw==","$type":"4"},{"$binary":"TCjFHw9nTsOYdNJmpPwa2A==","$type":"4"},{"$binary":"Waj76GBxRNiNLDKaM+6TRg==","$type":"4"},{"$binary":"xOKv3XJbSNOlYiUG3kcayA==","$type":"4"},{"$binary":"KhZtUXqYQc6kOMKSYyLPpg==","$type":"4"},{"$binary":"eJy0/3GRRriSVvWZdlzYEA==","$type":"4"}]},{"_id":{"$oid":"6107d557942a4b6254576ffc"},"asset_id":{"$binary":"+NW2To6nTv6KO4OL4R6S/A==","$type":"4"},"payload":{"title":"Leveraging relational autocorrelation with latent group models","authors":["Jennifer Neville","David D. Jensen"],"date":{"$date":"2005-08-02T00:00:00.000Z"},"pdf_url":"http://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=1090201","abstract":"The presence of autocorrelation provides a strong motivation for using relational learning and inference techniques. Autocorrelation is a statistical dependence between the values of the same variable on related entities and is a nearly ubiquitous characteristic of relational data sets. Recent research has explored the use of collective inference techniques to exploit this phenomenon. These techniques achieve significant performance gains by modeling observed correlations among class labels of related instances, but the models fail to capture a frequent cause of autocorrelation - the presence of underlying groups that influence the attributes on a set of entities. We propose a latent group model (LGM) for relational data, which discovers and exploits the hidden structures responsible for the observed autocorrelation among class labels. Modeling the latent group structure improves model performance, increases inference efficiency, and enhances our understanding of the datasets. We evaluate performance on three relational classification tasks and show that LGM outperforms models that ignore latent group structure, particularly when there is little information with which to seed inference.","arxiv_id":null,"doi":"10.1145/1090193.1090201","journal_title":"undefined"},"created_by":null,"proposed_to":[],"related_articles_were_imported":true,"id":null,"created_at":{"$date":"2021-08-02T11:21:59.555Z"},"cited_articles":[{"$binary":"is5Ld28hSMGZtIzAhHw/mA==","$type":"4"},{"$binary":"lPHWbweIR127ZQZoTbFS8w==","$type":"4"}]},{"_id":{"$oid":"6107d557942a4b6254576ffd"},"asset_id":{"$binary":"PTht29ljTFCastf2m5m/QQ==","$type":"4"},"payload":{"title":"Inferring Privacy Information from Social Networks","authors":["J. He","W. Chu","Zhenyu Liu"],"date":{"$date":"2006-08-02T00:00:00.000Z"},"pdf_url":"https://doi.org/10.1007/11760146_14","abstract":"Since privacy information can be inferred via social relations, the privacy confidentiality problem becomes increasingly challenging as online social network services are more popular. Using a Bayesian network approach to model the causal relations among people in social networks, we study the impact of prior probability, influence strength, and society openness to the inference accuracy on a real online social network. Our exper