m that of her community. We further develop a regularization technique to bias the model to learn more socially meaningful topics for each community. Our experiments on a Twitter dataset show that the CPI model outperforms other state-of-the-art models in topic learning and user classification tasks. We also demonstrate that the CPI model can effectively mine community interest through some representative case examples.","arxiv_id":null,"doi":"10.1007/978-3-319-18038-0_55","journal_title":"undefined"},"created_by":null,"proposed_to":[],"related_articles_were_imported":false,"id":null,"created_at":{"$date":"2021-08-02T13:10:39.129Z"},"cited_articles":[{"$binary":"547YxshSTvSre9siclIe+w==","$type":"4"}]},{"_id":{"$oid":"6107eecfb023a101bc07fb29"},"asset_id":{"$binary":"QXVwdcd1Rzqc8Y5i82ljlg==","$type":"4"},"payload":{"title":"Inferring user interests in the Twitter social network","authors":["P. Bhattacharya","M. B. Zafar","Niloy Ganguly","Saptarshi P. Ghosh","K. Gummadi"],"date":{"$date":"2014-08-02T00:00:00.000Z"},"pdf_url":"http://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=2645765","abstract":"We propose a novel mechanism to infer topics of interest of individual users in the Twitter social network. We observe that in Twitter, a user generally follows experts on various topics of her interest in order to acquire information on those topics. We use a methodology based on social annotations (proposed earlier by us) to first deduce the topical expertise of popular Twitter users, and then transitively infer the interests of the users who follow them. This methodology is a sharp departure from the traditional techniques of inferring interests of a user from the tweets that she posts or receives. We show that the topics of interest inferred by the proposed methodology are far superior than the topics extracted by state-of-the-art techniques such as using topic models (Labeled LDA) on tweets. Based upon the proposed methodology, we build a system Who Likes What, which can infer the inte