mal users. Using link creation timestamps, we verify that the large majority of links between Sybil accounts are created accidentally, unbeknownst to the attacker. Overall, only a very small portion of Sybil accounts are connected to other Sybils with social links. Our study shows that existing Sybil defenses are unlikely to succeed in today's OSNs, and we must design new techniques to effectively detect and defend against Sybil attacks.","arxiv_id":null,"doi":"10.1145/2068816.2068841","journal_title":"undefined"},"created_by":null,"proposed_to":[],"related_articles_were_imported":false,"id":null,"created_at":{"$date":"2021-08-02T13:11:39.652Z"},"cited_articles":[{"$binary":"NA1NExzKSTG3MycxxTHXTg==","$type":"4"}]},{"_id":{"$oid":"6107ef0cb023a101bc07fb7d"},"asset_id":{"$binary":"TgxEhRUESjCIbCFj+4UUmA==","$type":"4"},"payload":{"title":"Security Issues in Online Social Networks","authors":["Hongyu Gao","Jun Hu","Tuo Huang","Jingnan Wang","Y. Chen"],"date":{"$date":"2011-08-02T00:00:00.000Z"},"pdf_url":"http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/stamp/stamp.jsp?tp=&arnumber=5740826","abstract":"This article surveys the current state of security issues and available defense mechanisms regarding popular online social networks. It covers a wide variety of attacks and the corresponding defense mechanisms, if available. The authors organize these attacks into four categories - privacy breaches, viral marketing, network structural attacks, and malware attacks - and focus primarily on privacy concerns. They offer an in-depth discussion of each category and analyze the connections among the different security issues involved.","arxiv_id":null,"doi":"10.1109/MIC.2011.50","journal_title":"undefined"},"created_by":null,"proposed_to":[],"related_articles_were_imported":false,"id":null,"created_at":{"$date":"2021-08-02T13:11:40.036Z"},"cited_articles":[]},{"_id":{"$oid":"6107ef13b023a101bc07fb7e"},"asset_id":{"$binary":"DkrAeDyISluh85ccV6OWUA==","$type":"4"},"payload":{"title":"Social Network P