metrics on this group or on appropriate homogeneous spaces. In particular, we describe how Arnold's approach to the Euler equations as geodesic flows of one-sided invariant metrics extends from Lie groups to homogeneous spaces. We also show that the above three cases describe all generic bihamiltonian systems which are related to the Virasoro group and can be integrated by the translation argument principle: they correspond precisely to the three different types of generic Virasoro orbits. Finally, we discuss interrelation between the above metrics and Kahler structures on Virasoro orbits as well as open questions regarding integrable systems corresponding to a finer classification of the orbits.","arxiv_id":null,"doi":"10.1016/S0001-8708(02)00063-4","journal_title":"undefined"},"created_by":null,"proposed_to":[],"related_articles_were_imported":false,"id":null,"created_at":{"$date":"2021-08-02T13:20:25.485Z"},"cited_articles":[]},{"_id":{"$oid":"6107f119b023a101bc07fc8c"},"asset_id":{"$binary":"ab0rDwm2QPmEoQOrlM2yeQ==","$type":"4"},"payload":{"title":"Smooth global Lagrangian flow for the 2D Euler and second-grade fluid equations","authors":["S. Shkoller"],"date":{"$date":"2001-08-02T00:00:00.000Z"},"pdf_url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/math/0007027.pdf","abstract":"Abstract We present a very simple proof of the global existence of a C ∞ Lagrangian flow map for the 2D Euler and second-grade fluid equations (on a compact Riemannian manifold with boundary) which has C ∞ dependence on initial data u 0 in the class of H s divergence-free vector fields for s > 2.","arxiv_id":null,"doi":"10.1016/S0893-9659(00)00190-7","journal_title":"undefined"},"created_by":null,"proposed_to":[],"related_articles_were_imported":false,"id":null,"created_at":{"$date":"2021-08-02T13:20:25.600Z"},"cited_articles":[]},{"_id":{"$oid":"6107f119b023a101bc07fc8d"},"asset_id":{"$binary":"tOutoYywR/STuavmg1yPYA==","$type":"4"},"payload":{"title":"Wave breaking for nonlinear nonlocal shallow water equ