eful, and hence that it should be beneficial to include all fringe nodes that are available. However, we find that this is not true; in fact, there is substantial variability in the value of the fringe nodes for prediction. Once an algorithm is selected, in some datasets, including any additional data from the fringe can actually hurt prediction performance; in other datasets, including some amount of fringe information is useful before prediction performance saturates or even declines; and in further cases, including the entire fringe leads to the best performance. While such variety might seem surprising, we show that these behaviors are exhibited by simple random graph models.","arxiv_id":null,"doi":"10.1145/3308558.3313626","journal_title":"undefined"},"created_by":null,"proposed_to":[],"related_articles_were_imported":false,"id":null,"created_at":{"$date":"2021-08-02T13:24:57.670Z"},"cited_articles":[{"$binary":"C3tPDxiBQfWqJepaMpuwxA==","$type":"4"}]},{"_id":{"$oid":"6107f22ab023a101bc07fd33"},"asset_id":{"$binary":"4xX4f21kSmipJM4a/HY29A==","$type":"4"},"payload":{"title":"Will Scale-Free Popularity Develop Scale-Free Geo-Social Networks?","authors":["D. Liu","V. Fodor","L. Rasmussen"],"date":{"$date":"2019-08-02T00:00:00.000Z"},"pdf_url":"http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/stamp/stamp.jsp?tp=&arnumber=8368313","abstract":"Empirical results show that spatial factors such as distance, population density and communication range affect our social activities, also reflected by the development of ties in social networks. This motivates the need for social network models that take these spatial factors into account. Therefore, in this paper we propose a gravity-low-based geo-social network model, where connections develop according to the popularity of the individuals, but are constrained through their geographic distance and the surrounding population density. Specifically, we consider a power-law distributed popularity, and random node positions governed by a Poisson poi