ctually hurt prediction performance; in other datasets, including some amount of fringe information is useful before prediction performance saturates or even declines; and in further cases, including the entire fringe leads to the best performance. While such variety might seem surprising, we show that these behaviors are exhibited by simple random graph models.","arxiv_id":null,"doi":"10.1145/3308558.3313626","journal_title":"undefined"},"created_by":null,"proposed_to":[],"related_articles_were_imported":false,"id":null,"created_at":{"$date":"2021-08-02T13:25:30.851Z"},"cited_articles":[{"$binary":"C3tPDxiBQfWqJepaMpuwxA==","$type":"4"}]},{"_id":{"$oid":"6107f24bb023a101bc07fd5d"},"asset_id":{"$binary":"C3xgphJ7SZaBYyG1pqK0Zw==","$type":"4"},"payload":{"title":"The role and potential of social networks sites in tertiary education","authors":["D. Vrontis","M. Viassone","A. Thrassou"],"date":{"$date":"2018-08-02T00:00:00.000Z"},"pdf_url":"https://doi.org/10.7433/S97.2015.05","abstract":"Purpose of the paper : Social Networks Sites (SNSs) are becoming very popular among students and constitute a promising field for tertiary education evolution. This research aims at assessing the usage of social networks for educational aims and at evaluating the perception of university students towards this kind of usage. Methodology : Methodologically, the paper rests on an extensive, comprehensive and comparative theoretical research on the subject, as well as on primary research involving the in-depth survey of 125 university students in Northern Italy. Findings : The findings underline the importance of utilizing SNSs to improve educational communications, sharing of information, student-student and student-educator interaction, efficiency, polyphony and more. The research also stressed the need for SNS adoption to be specific and in accordance with both student and lecturer attitudes, competences and limitations, as well other therein specified stakeholders and added values.  R