nd noisy data, based on comparisons with the theoretical MI estimates, which can be computed analytically, as well with linear correlation and Kendall's $\\ensuremath{\\tau}$. Here we consider smaller data sizes, such as 50, 100, and 1000, and within this study we characterize 50 and 100 data points as very short and 1000 as short. We consider a broader class of functions, specifically linear, quadratic, periodic, and chaotic, contaminated with artificial noise with varying noise-to-signal ratios. Our results indicate KDEs as the best choice for very short data at relatively high noise-to-signal levels whereas the performance of KNNs is the best for very short data at relatively low noise levels as well as for short data consistently across noise levels. In addition, the optimal smoothing parameter of a Gaussian kernel appears to be the best choice for KDEs while three nearest neighbors appear optimal for KNNs. Thus, in situations where the approximate data sizes are known in advance and exploratory data analysis and/or domain knowledge can be used to provide a priori insights into the noise-to-signal ratios, the results in the paper point to a way forward for automating the process of MI estimation.","arxiv_id":null,"doi":"10.1103/PhysRevE.76.026209","journal_title":"Physical Review E"},"created_by":null,"proposed_to":[],"related_articles_were_imported":false,"id":null,"created_at":{"$date":"2021-08-02T13:29:52.348Z"},"cited_articles":[{"$binary":"Va1Vm0T/QSmUHY06gzkRRA==","$type":"4"},{"$binary":"0b8q2XIYS2mnih8EzCEf7Q==","$type":"4"}]},{"_id":{"$oid":"6107f3e8b023a101bc07fe31"},"asset_id":{"$binary":"BzPIh7X5SvOZ8N1vujj9sQ==","$type":"4"},"payload":{"title":"Structural Attack to Anonymous Graph of Social Networks","authors":["Zhu, Tieying","Wang, Shanshan","Li, Xiangtao","Zhou, Zhiguo","Zhang, Riming"],"date":{"$date":"2013-11-21T00:00:00.000Z"},"pdf_url":"https://downloads.hindawi.com/journals/mpe/2013/237024.pdf","abstract":"With the rapid development of social